I&#39;m no expert in this area but I assume that the &lt;kbd&gt;Option&lt;/kbd&gt;+&lt;kbd&gt;left/right&lt;/kbd&gt; keybinding is being handled by your shell - vscode has nothing to do with that.  So you won&#39;t find a command that vscode is using to skip forward/back in the terminal.

But you can implement one yourself by sending the shell control codes to the shell with your chosen keybindings.  Like:

 

    {
      &quot;key&quot;: &quot;ctrl+b&quot;,
      &quot;command&quot;: &quot;workbench.action.terminal.sendSequence&quot;,
      &quot;args&quot;: {
          &quot;text&quot;: &quot;\u001b[;5D&quot;
      },
      &quot;when&quot;: &quot;terminalFocus &amp;&amp; !terminalTextSelected&quot;
    },
    {
      &quot;key&quot;: &quot;ctrl+f&quot;,
      &quot;command&quot;: &quot;workbench.action.terminal.sendSequence&quot;,
      &quot;args&quot;: {
          &quot;text&quot;: &quot;\u001b[;5C&quot;
      },
      &quot;when&quot;: &quot;terminalFocus &amp;&amp; !terminalTextSelected&quot;
    },

Swap `cmd` for `ctrl` depending on your OS.  You didn&#39;t say what shell you are using but it works on git bash and cmd.exe on Windows - all I can test on here.

`\u001b[` is the control sequence introducer, so that what follows is interpreted as a control sequence not literal charachters.

The `5D` is the same as &lt;kbd&gt;Ctrl&lt;/kbd&gt;+&lt;kbd&gt;leftarrow&lt;/kbd&gt;.  The `5` is &lt;kbd&gt;Ctrl&lt;/kbd&gt; and can be found in the second link below&#39;s &quot;PC-Style Function Keys&quot; section.  The `D` is cursor back.  See &quot;Functions using CSI , ordered by the final character(s)&quot;.  I believe the `;` is necessary to indicate that the following is a control character, in this case 5 or the Control Key, and not a number 5.


See https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/editor/integrated-terminal#_send-text-from-a-keybinding and its control code links like http://invisible-island.net/xterm/ctlseqs/ctlseqs.html.

There is normally no difference in the implementation of an aggregation versus an association because their semantic difference is normally not relevant in the code of an app.

An aggregation is a special form of association with the intended meaning of a *part-whole-relationship*, where the parts of a whole can be shared with other wholes. For instance, we can model an aggregation between the classes `DegreeProgram` and `Course`, as shown in the following diagram, since a course is part of a degree program and a course can be shared among two or more degree programs (e.g. an engineering degree could share a C programming course with a computer science degree). 

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

Modeling the special relationship between `DegreeProgram` and `Course` in this way conveys some intended meaning, but does not have to be, and is typically not, reflected in the implementation code, which may look as follows:

    class DegreeProgram {    
      private List&lt;Course&gt; courses;
      ...
    }



